description.text: I designed this to make leveling my HBP a little easier. Once everything is installed the level can be adjusted very easily. The HBP can be installed or removed easily also. I have know idea if this will work on the ABP but should work on the acrylic platform. You have to use a 3 point leveling system though, 2 corner adjusters on the front and a straight one in the middle in the rear. If you put corner ones in the rear they may hit the Z rods, or any extensions such as Jetguys brass tube Z extenders.

Print 2 corner sets and 1 straight set. I had to design a imperial size also because I couldn't find M3 hardware locally. So I substituted a 6-32 for my rear adjuster. Because of the level of my HBP the original M3 hardware on the rear adjuster just barely made the threads. The front are still the original M3 hardware I received with my aluminum build plate. So if you have similar problems you may have to print out the inches set(s). 
You may have to clean out the holes and enlarge the one on the top of the brackets. Press the nut into the thumb wheels. Thread the bolt down through the plastic nut and the metal nut to make sure everything aligns and also to thread the plastic nut. I left this tight so that there is some friction to prevent the thumb wheel from turning once adjusted. Glue the thumb wheel to the nut. Snap the thumb wheel assembly onto the bracket. With the HBP removed slide the adjusters into place. Place the HBP into place and push down until the threads catch. Using the thumb wheels screw the HBP down and then adjust the level.

description.text:
Anyone who has ever had to walk on crutches knows how difficult it can be to carry things, especially a cup. To solve this common problem, Team Carry Crutches developed a self-stabilizing cup holder that attaches to a crutch and can hold a beverage without spilling it. The team designed a 3D printed gimbal inspired by those used to steady a camera on an aerial drone. The team developed two versions of the cup holder: a mechanical version that costs only $15 in materials and combines 3D printed parts with ball bearings, and an electronic version features a Raspberry Pi, servo motors, and an accelerometer and costs $30 to build. "We know that sometimes, helping people do the simplest tasks can have a tremendous impact, that's why our team created the Carry Crutches," said Tomas Garces, a design engineer at General Electric Firstbuild. "To have a person on the team who has a need for the device was integral to our design process and we look forward to seeing how people on Thingiverse improve upon it.” The 3D design files for Carry Crutches are available on Thingiverse.  
Team members: Benoy Bhagattjee, Daisy Bermudez, Ilan Sherman, Maayan Dremer, Matthew Wasala, Tomas Garces.

title: Aluminatus Corner Clamps With Height Adjuster & 1mm taller clamps

description.text:
This is a remix of GKbeers bed corners and clamps.
I added two holes so you can add a 5mm x .8 pitch adjuster bolt on the outer corner or on the inside. My heater plate is a bit smaller than my glass, so I chose to use the inside hole. This adjuster bolt will require you to drill a hole at each corner. The hole size in the corner is such that the bolt can thread in tightly and require no further hardware to stay snug. The F-300 parts are the fixed pieces that get attached and tightened on the rear and along one side. These remain stationary. The A-300 are put on the front and the other side and are snugged down lightly once your glass or print surface is level. I added 1mm to the height on the part that contacts the glass. My glass has a rounded edge and the extra height was needed for better grab. I also added a tiny angle to the face of the clamping part to help if you have rounded glass edges. It will be fine for flat edge print plates also. I increased the text size on the clamping parts for better readability. (8) M3 x 16mm .5 pitch screws and hex nuts are needed to complete a full set of corners.

.2mm layer height
ABS
40% infill The best way to locate your holes is to mount the corner and snug down two F-300 clamps on it. This will pull it to optimal position. You may need to file the mounting hole a little if it is not coming out to perfectly mate with the F-300's. There can be a small variance in beds. Next just use a transfer punch to make a perfect location for drilling. Remove the corner before drilling (you dont want to ruin your tight fit for the adjuster bolt). I chose a drill bit that left the hole with just barely enough drag on the bolt that you have to twist it through. I also chose to put Heli-coils in the bed so there is no nut to deal with when installing the corners. This will also allow me to make a knob later for the adjustment with nothing in the way. The helicoils were installed with red loctite and let cure before installing. I used M5 x 8mm bolts to secure the corners with the Heli-coils. If you have a print surface that is bigger than 300mm, you may need to shorten the clamp faces a little. I did not make 305mm parts because I do not have 305mm glass. I rounded off the adjuster bolts on the belt sander so they would not dig and I also added two layers of kaptan tape to the corners for extra protection.

The need knower of this challenge has a neuromuscular condition, and due to her disability, she sits in her wheelchair 14–16 hours every day. Sitting in the same position for too long can lead to a list of dangerous health issues, which are magnified by people who have no sensation in their lower body. 
Team Smart Seat developed a solution that helps people who sit in their wheel chair for a long time to manage their weight distribution. The team developed thin stickers with sensors that are held in place by a 3D printed frame on a wheelchair’s seat to map out the pressure points then send the data to to a smartphone app to prevent pain, pressure sores, and other health risks. The Smartphone app can also automatically alert the user when it's time to move. The Smart Seat solution is a Google.org innovation award winner.

description.text:
This printed medical linac, which can rotate around the patient, was
designed by a summer student (Cameron Tharp) at the University of
Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center. The concept is for patient
education, but might also be useful for trainee dosimetrists or other
staff in radiation oncology. Also see our CT scanner.

These instructions refer to the components in the figure.
1) Attach Component #6 to the interior notch of Component #5
with an adhesive material such as glue.
2) Lay Component #4 onto the appropriate raised peg of
Component #7.
3) Slide the attached pieces (components 5 & 6) into the hollow
slot of Component #4 to create Completed Component #1.
4) Attach Component #1 onto the appropriate raised peg of
Component #7
5) Take Component #3 and insert one end of Component #2 into
the circular indentation located on the back wall of Component #3.
6) Once Components 2 & 3 are joined, insert the open end of
Component #2 into the hole in Component #1.
7) Attach both parts of Component #8 onto the sides of
Component #3. When attached, they form Complete Component #3

This is a remix of Prax's adjustable mobius mount for KipK's tricopter design (brocopter).  It allows the angle the mobius camera to be adjust while still keeping it isolated from vibration.  No modifications are needed to the brocopter.  Just replace the original with this assembled mount.  
This could easily be used for other multirotors as well as long as the spacing of the 10mm vibration dampers is the same.  
I've flown this on my tricopter and it works great.  The angle holds even during aggressive maneuvers.  Being able to angle the camera down slightly really helps for taking aerial stills, but I can easily angle it up for high speed proximity flights.  Hope this works well for you as well!

Print all three pieces.  The mobius tray will need to be acetone welded or super glued to the hing piece.  Just stick the flat sides together.  Make sure the "latches" that hold the mobius into the tray are extended beyond the front edge of the hinge piece.  
Use M3 screws to attach the hinge piece to the base mount.  Set to the desired angle, tighten the screws, and enjoy!

description.text: A beefed-up version of Jeremy Blum's neat Raspberry Pi case with a lid designed to hold the Adafruit 16x2 character LCD. Print me!

I meant to release a revision that added screw holes, but it was never a pressing issue so I never finished the design.

remixed_from.title: Power Supply Mounting Brackets for Prusa IT2

description.text: My 12V 20A power supply that I got from amazon didn't have the same screw holes that all of the other PSU mounts had.  The most succesful strategy I had was to use the holes on the bottom of the PSU.  I made this parametric in openscad so that you can easily accomodate any sized PSU.  It mounts below the y carriage.

Print 4 (or more) copies of this.  Requires 1 M3 screw (and I recommedn a washer) for each copy.  Flip the power supply upside down and loosely screw in each mounting bracket so there is plenty of play and they swing from side to side, To install, turn your prusa upside down, place the power supply underneath the y carriage wher you expect to install it, place the mounting brackets on the m8 rods, push down and tightend the m3 screws.  
Note: On my power supply, I had serious problems (arduino would power off) when I would screw the screws too deeply into the power supply unit.  Use nuts or washers to offset the screws (or use nylon m3 screws) if this happens to you.

description.text: DPHS

The XRace360 is a simple lightweight quadcopter frame in the 250mm racing class designed with Autodesks Fusion 360. Since Quadrocopter Races become more and more popular I decided to make one to have some fun in the air. The aim is to develop a robust and slight frame which is easy to manufacture at low costs. Therefore I decided a frame, which can be lasercutted and 3D printed. It should have enought place for a FPV (First Person View) system and additional hardware like a GPS, a Telemetry transmitter and 4K Cameras. Finally a nice case and wings for the arms are in production. A stealth optic like the F-117A Nighthawk or sth. like the DJI Inspire would be awesome. The Frame should be printed in ABS or Nylon with more than 40% Infill rate and honeycomb pattern. Hardware of my copter:
3D printed 250mm Frame
Micro HKPilot Mega Flight Controller with Ardupilots APM 3.2 Software.
4x Multistar 2206 2150KV Baby Beast V2 Brushless Motors with
4x 12 Ampere Afro Speed Controllers (with SimonK Firmware)
4x 5030 5 inch Composite or Carbon Propellers
FrSky Reciever (Rx) with Telemetry port
?x 1300mAh - 1800mAh 3S Zippy LiPo Battery Additional HW
LEA-6H GPS with Compass
915Mhz Telemetry Kit
5,8G Video Transmission System (FPV) with Cloverleaf antennas and ground station (i.e. FPV Goggles)
GoPro Hero Camera
Flashing Lights
and more With this Hardware one is also able to let this copter fly fully autonomous. Setting up waypoints or a "follow me" function is available. The copter comes with nice features like RTL (return to launch) and loiter mode.
Finally there are more cool pros for a small racing copter like transportability and speed. More facts:
My measured weight before the flight with all components assembled (without additional hw) is just 460 gramms.
The costs for the electonical parts needed is around 200EUR.
The flight time is about minimum 3 minutes up to 10 min. (calculated with a 1300mAh battery from acrobatic flight to hover mode)
The calculated maximum speed is around 70 km/h with at least a 10m/s climb rate.
I am using the Turnigy 9XR Radio with a FrSky DJT Module and Bluetooth. First Flight Test:
https://youtu.be/o6V5nyzyZcA Fusion 360 Gallery:
https://fusion360.autodesk.com/users/fabian-schurig Created with Autodesk Fusion 360.

The Frame should be printed in ABS or Nylon with more than 40% Infill rate and honeycomb pattern. Please rotate and center each part to ground.
Every part is printable without support material. You can also CNC mill this frame.

title: Solidoodle X-carriage and new printable extruder assembly.

description.text:
This is for advanced users only, I will not be providing detailed instructions on assembly at this point, as it is Version 1.0 and requires wider testing then just me. I built this for my Solidoodle 3, and I am fairly sure it will works on a Solidoodle 2 but need confirmation. This is a printable replacement for the Solidoodle x-axis carriage and extruder assembly. This uses few pieces and offers more precise and permanent adjustment of the rear pinch blocks for the x-axis carriage. With this carriage assembly I am reliably printing at 100mm/s and fast moves are going at 120mm/s I have not tested higher speeds yet. I am looking forward to any constructive critasism that may be given too me.
I have also included a dimensioned drawing of the carriage extruder area, I know the numbers are a little odd, but there are some tight spaces in the extruder assembly. Let me know if you find any issues or need a hand at getting it working properly in this thread at soliforum. http://www.soliforum.com/topic/2311/entirely-new-printable-extruder-and-xcarriage-assembly/

Print a very strong part. there are some bending forces involved in this kind of print.  
Use caution on the pinch screws, the holes thru the carriage are a very tight fit on purpose to keep the lower carriage block from chattering at high speeds.  
There are 2 versions of the Extruder Base one with a ATX 4-pin panel mount holder if you change your extruder connection wires. One with out the Wire holder.   
It is imperative that the carriage itself end up very flat. In a few of my tests I used a warped part on purpose and got some interesting ridge patterns going on.

//execute time code
} if(digitalRead(WEATHERPIN)!=HIGH){
//execute weather code
} UPDATE
